| `ggplot2::autoplot()` | 九덢잺 | 九덢잺 |
| `ggplot2::fortify()` | 九덢잺 to **sf** via `sf::st_as_sf()` | To a **tibble** with coordinates. |
| `ggplot2::geom_*()` | 九덢잺 `geom_spatvector()` | 九덢잺 `geom_spatraster()` and `geom_spatraster_rgb()`. |
| `generics::tidy()` | 九덢잺 | 九덢잺 |
| `generics::glance()` | 九덢잺 | 九덢잺 |
| `generics::required_pkgs()` | 九덢잺 | 九덢잺 |

The following sections show some of these methods in action.

### `SpatRaster` objects

This example uses a `SpatRaster`:

```{r}
#| label: simple_example
library(terra)
f <- system.file("extdata/cyl_temp.tif", package = "tidyterra")

temp <- rast(f)

temp

mod <- temp |>
  select(-1) |>
  mutate(newcol = tavg_06 - tavg_05) |>
  relocate(newcol, .before = 1) |>
  replace_na(list(newcol = 3)) |>
  rename(difference = newcol)

mod
```

In this example we:

-   Removed the first layer (`tavg_04`).
-   Created a new layer `newcol` as the difference between `tavg_06` and
    `tavg_05`.
-   Relocated `newcol` to be the first layer.
-   Replaced `NA` values in `newcol` with `3`.
-   Renamed `newcol` to `difference`.

Throughout these steps, core properties of the `SpatRaster` (number of cells,
rows, columns, extent, resolution and CRS) remain unchanged. Other verbs
such as `filter()`, `slice()` or `drop_na()` may alter these properties in a
manner analogous to how row operations affect data frames.

### `SpatVector` objects

Most **dplyr** and **tidyr** verbs work with `SpatVector` objects, so you can
arrange, group and summarize their attributes.

```{r}
#| label: newpatv-methods
lux <- system.file("ex/lux.shp", package = "terra")

v_lux <- vect(lux)

v_lux |>
  # Create categories.
  mutate(gr = cut(POP / 1000, 5)) |>
  group_by(gr) |>
  # Summarize by group.
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    tot_pop = sum(POP),
    mean_area = mean(AREA)
  ) |>
  # Arrange groups.
  arrange(desc(gr))
```

As with `SpatRaster`, essential properties such as geometry and CRS are
preserved during these operations.

## Plotting with ggplot2

### `SpatRaster` objects

When a `SpatRaster` has a CRS defined (`terra::crs(a_rast) != ""`), the geom
uses `ggplot2::coord_sf()` and can be reprojected to match other spatial layers.

```{r}
#| label: fig-faceted
#| fig-cap: Faceted map using a SpatRaster.
#| fig-asp: 0.3
library(ggplot2)

# Faceted SpatRaster.

ggplot() +
  geom_spatraster(data = temp) +
  facet_wrap(~lyr) +
  scale_fill_whitebox_c(
    palette = "muted",
    na.value = "white"
  )
```

```{r}
#| label: fig-contourlines
#| fig-cap: Contour line plot for a SpatRaster.
# Contour lines for a specific layer.

f_volcano <- system.file("extdata/volcano2.tif", package = "tidyterra")
volcano2 <- rast(f_volcano)

ggplot() +
  geom_spatraster(data = volcano2) +
  geom_spatraster_contour(data = volcano2, breaks = seq(80, 200, 5)) +
  scale_fill_whitebox_c() +
  coord_sf(expand = FALSE) +
  labs(fill = "elevation")
```

```{r}
#| label: fig-contourfilled
#| fig-cap: Filled contour plot for a SpatRaster.

# Filled contours.

ggplot() +
  geom_spatraster_contour_filled(data = volcano2) +
  scale_fill_whitebox_d(palette = "atlas") +
  labs(fill = "elevation")
```

**tidyterra** also supports RGB `SpatRaster` objects for imagery:

```{r}
#| label: fig-rgb
#| fig-cap: Map combining an RGB SpatRaster and a SpatVector.
# Read a vector.

f_v <- system.file("extdata/cyl.gpkg", package = "tidyterra")
v <- vect(f_v)

# Read a tile.
f_rgb <- system.file("extdata/cyl_tile.tif", package = "tidyterra")

r_rgb <- rast(f_rgb)

rgb_plot <- ggplot(v) +
  geom_spatraster_rgb(data = r_rgb) +
  geom_spatvector(fill = NA, size = 1)

rgb_plot
```

**tidyterra** includes color scales suitable for hypsometric and bathymetric
maps:

```{r}
#| label: fig-hypso
#| fig-cap: Map of Asia including hypsometric tints.
#| fig-asp: 0.65
asia <- rast(system.file("extdata/asia.tif", package = "tidyterra"))

asia

ggplot() +
  geom_spatraster(data = asia) +
  scale_fill_hypso_tint_c(
    palette = "gmt_globe",
    labels = scales::label_number(),
    # Further refinements
    breaks = c(-10000, -5000, 0, 2000, 5000, 8000),
    guide = guide_colorbar(reverse = TRUE)
  ) +
  labs(
    fill = "elevation (m)",
    title = "Hypsometric map of Asia"
  ) +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.title.position = "top",
    legend.key.width = rel(3),
    legend.ticks = element_line(colour = "black", linewidth = 0.3),
    legend.direction = "horizontal"
  )
```

### `SpatVector` objects

Plot `SpatVector` objects with `geom_spatvector()`:

```{r}
#| label: fig-lux_ggplot
#| fig-cap: Choropleth map with a SpatVector object.
lux <- system.file("ex/lux.shp", package = "terra")

v_lux <- terra::vect(lux)

ggplot(v_lux) +
  geom_spatvector(aes(fill = POP), color = "white") +
  geom_spatvector_text(aes(label = NAME_2), color = "grey90") +
  scale_fill_binned(labels = scales::number_format()) +
  coord_sf(crs = 3857)
```

Internally, **tidyterra** converts `terra::vect()` output to **sf** with
`sf::st_as_sf()` and then uses `ggplot2::geom_sf()` to render the layer.

You can also aggregate `SpatVector` objects easily:

```{r}
#| label: fig-aggregate
#| fig-cap:
#|    - Dissolving SpatVector objects by group.
#|    - Dissolving SpatVector objects by group, keeping internal boundaries.
# Dissolve by group.
v_lux |>
  # Create categories.
  mutate(gr = cut(POP / 1000, 5)) |>
  group_by(gr) |>
  # Summarize by group.
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    tot_pop = sum(POP),
    mean_area = mean(AREA)
  ) |>
  ggplot() +
  geom_spatvector(aes(fill = tot_pop), color = "black") +
  geom_spatvector_label(aes(label = gr)) +
  coord_sf(crs = 3857)

# Repeat while keeping internal boundaries.
v_lux |>
  # Create categories.
  mutate(gr = cut(POP / 1000, 5)) |>
  group_by(gr) |>
  # Summarize by group without dissolving.
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    tot_pop = sum(POP),
    mean_area = mean(AREA),
    .dissolve = FALSE
  ) |>
  ggplot() +
  geom_spatvector(aes(fill = tot_pop), color = "black") +
  geom_spatvector_label(aes(label = gr)) +
  coord_sf(crs = 3857)
```
